 Duke Dai of Song (ruler of the state of Song, reigned 799‚Äď766  BC ). Yan's grandson Le Ju (ś®āŤéí) inherited Le (ś®ā) as his surname.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname Śčí: (i) from the second element of the placename Shu-Le (ÁĖŹŚčí), an ancient state (located in present-day Xinjiang Uyghur autonomous region) during the Western Han dynasty (206  BC ‚Äď25  AD ). (ii) a surname near the Bohai Sea region during the Han dynasty (206  BC ‚Äď220  AD ). (iii) a surname traced back to the Hun ethnic group in northern China during the Jin dynasty (265‚Äď420  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Yue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Chi, Feng, Gang, Wei, Chun, Guo, Jin, Kin, Ping, Yan, Yun, Zhang, Chau, Du, Hau, Hung, My, Sau.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname Ś≤≥ (or Ś∂Ĺ), meaning ‚Äėhigh mountain‚Äô in Chinese: traced back to Si Yue (ŚõõŚ≤≥ or ŚõõŚ∂Ĺ), said to be the title of an official post in charge of sacrificial rituals on the site of famous mountains during the reign of the legendary Emperor Yao (<i>c.</i> 24th century  BC ) and Emperor Shun (<i>c.</i> 23rd century  BC )."]},{"name":"Lok","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Ping, Tat, Wing, Ying Lin, Chi Ming, Ching Wah, Chun, Chung Man, Han, Kam, Kam Tim, Kin.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname ś®ā, see   Le   1.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames ťôł, ťĻŅ, ťÄĮ and Á¶Ą, see   Lu   5 and (7-9)."]},{"name":"Li","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ming, Li, Jian, Hong, Yan, Ping, Jing, Yong, Ying, Hui, Jin, Min, Chung.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname śĚé, meaning ‚Äėplum‚Äô: (i) said to have been adopted in place of the Chinese surname ÁźÜ (also pronounced Li; meaning ‚Äėrules‚Äô in Chinese) by Li Zhen (Śą©Ť≤ě), son of an official called Li Zheng (ÁźÜŚĺĶ) in the late Shang dynasty (1600‚Äď1046  BC ). It is said that Li Zhen's father incurred the displeasure of King Zhou of Shang (died 1046  BC ) and Li Zhen fled to a wasteland area, where he survived on wild plums. After his return to civilization, he changed his surname to Li (śĚé ‚Äėplum‚Äô), a word with the same pronunciation. The original surname, ÁźÜ, is said to be from Li Guan (ÁźÜŚģė), the name of a post of officials in charge of legislation in ancient China. Li Er (śĚéŤÄ≥), also known as Lao Tzu or Lao Zi, traditionally regarded as the founder of Taoism, is believed to have been a descendant of Li Zhen. (ii) adopted as a surname by the Chi Li (ŚŹĪśĚé) family from the Xianbei ethnic group during the Northern Wei dynasty (386‚Äď534  AD ). (iii) in the early years of the Tang dynasty (618‚Äď907  AD ), sixteen high officials with different surnames were granted the surname Li (śĚé), the surname of the royal family of the Tang dynasty, by Emperor Taizong of Tang (died 649  BC ), because of their contributions to the establishment of the Tang regime. (iv) the surname can also be traced back to several minority ethnic groups in ancient China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname ťĽé, meaning ‚Äėblack‚Äô or ‚Äėmultitude‚Äô in ancient Chinese: (i) from Li (ťĽé), the name of an ancient state (located in Changzhi in Shanxi province) during the Shang dynasty (1600‚Äď1046  BC ), which was annexed in the Western Zhou dynasty (1046‚Äď771  BC ) and later granted to Fengshu, also known as Li Hou (ťĽéšĺĮ, 'Marquis Li'). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Su Li (Áī†ťĽé) family, members of the Xianbei ethnic group, during the Northern Wei dynasty (386‚Äď534  AD )."]}]},{"name":"Wake","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names ¬© Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","occupational name for ‚Äė(man of) the watch‚Äô, from Middle English <i>wak</i>, <i>wake</i> ‚Äėwake, vigil, watch, period of guard duty‚Äô (Old English <i>wacu</i>, Old Norse <i>vaka</i>). It alternates with the synonymous Middle English <i>wache</i> (Old English <i>wacce</i>), hence the variant <b>Watch</b>. The surname was also interchangeable with   Waite   (the equivalent Old French term) which, like <i>Wake</i>, was sometimes translated as Latin <i>vigil</i> ‚Äė(one who is) watchful, alert‚Äô. Compare the synonymous   Vail  . When the bearers had high social status, the surname probably denoted an officer with responsibility for the security of a castle, town, or royal person. Compare   Wakeman  .","variant of   Wack  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vail","meanings":["English: occupational name from Old French <i>de la veille</i> ‚Äėof the watch, watchman‚Äô, with loss of <i>de</i>; compare   Wake  . There has been some confusion with the topographic name   Vale   and the nickname   Veal  .","Scottish: shortened and altered form of   McPhail  , Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Ph√†il</b> ‚Äėson of Paul‚Äô.","Irish: variant of   Veale  ."]},{"name":"Waite","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name for a watchman, either in a town or castle, from Anglo-Norman French <i>waite</i> ‚Äėwatchman, member of the watch‚Äô (of ancient Germanic origin; compare   Wachter  ). In the Middle Ages the town waits typically combined the functions of watchmen and musicians through being trumpeters or pipers. There may also have been some late confusion with   White   or   Wheat  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabella","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names ¬© Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."],"variants":[{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Isabella de Sacre le Wake was born about 1150, in Bedfordshire, England, her father, Hugh Wake, was 51 and her mother, Lady Joan Stuteville, was 46. She had at least 1 son with Simon de Beauchamp. She died in 1207, in Bedford, Bedfordshire, England, at the age of 58